. NULLs proposal:
1. Implement comparators, which allows NULL.
2. In select() and get() check if index allows NULL (at least one indexed field allows NULL) and if a key contains NULL then return empty sey, becuse NULL in the key would not be equal, greater or lesser than any value in its column.
3. Make an option for select(): {exact = boolean}. If exact == true, then do not check NULL in keys.
4. Make for all NULL-possible indexes new comparators: tuple_compare(NULL, NULL) == -1,
tuple_compare_with_key(NULL, NULL) == 0 (see struct key_def). In such a case select(exact = true) works automatically, because it uses tuple_compare_with_key(), and an unique NULL-possible index can store multiple NULLs, because to save a new tuple with NULL it used tuple_compare().. Assume, that there is a sequence of UPSERTs of the same key. And in the middle of the sequence one UPSERT is incorrect. What to do with the newer UPSERTs?
- Drop all the newer UPSERTs. Then the user must explicitly REPLACE or DELETE the key to fix the error.
- Skip only invalid UPSERT. This way seems to be unrealizable. Such sequence of UPSERTs can be merged in one UPSERT during compaction or dump, and it is impossible to split the merged UPSERTs back to delete only one invalid UPSERT.. Need some research. The main idea - if the UPSERT is broken and it had been commited, possibly the best solution is to discard all newer UPSERTs, including from newer transactions, until REPLACE/DELETE is commited.
The main problem is how to report this problem. We cannot report for each newer upsert the error, because upserts RPS can be very big and the log size would grow very fast.
