Why is it needed?
Sometimes it is needed to send some intermediate results from long
poll request. Or to create a watcher on a server side, which
listens for some events and sends notifications to a client.
Design and implementation
Common algorithm is quite simple: box.session.push encodes a
message in IPROTO_PUSH key and sends it to a client socket.
Client socket can be in a text mode (a client sends Lua code as a
text, and expects the same result as from Lua console), and in a
binary mode.
In a binary mode a socket can not be accessed directly by TX
thread. And push must write its data into obuf, not to socket.
Obuf is not accessible from a session, so it is proposed to add
iproto to a struct session as a member of struct session owner.
Another issue with iproto is that just writing into obuf is not
enough to triggers its flush into a socket. TX thread must notify
IProto thread about new data. It can be done via special cmsg.
In a text mode a socket can be accessed from TX thread, so it is
enough to write into it in blocking mode right in push call.
